Overview¶

The Capstone project is designed to undertake a multi-faceted project that demonstrates our understanding and mastery of the key conceptual and technological aspects of Deep Learning and targets to develop an understanding of how challenging human-level problems can be approached and solved using a combination of tools and techniques.

Project Objectives¶

Design a ML/DL based chatbot utility which can help the professionals to highlight the safety risk as per the incident description.

Our Approach Summary¶

  • Import the data

    We loaded the csv file as pandas dataframe to use it for all our analysis and modeling purpouses.

  • Data Cleansing

    Cleaned the data before starting the analysis to avoid running into semantic errors.

  • Data Preprocessing

    Initial level of data preprocessing was performed to change categorical features into encoded features. Changed DateTime features to more meaningful variables (quarter, day of week, month & year)

  • Exploratory Data Analysis

    Detailed EDA was performed on every existing & derived feature to get insights out of the data using interactive & dynamic plots. The conclusive insights are provided below every chart for better understanding

  • NLP Preprocessing

    The NLP preprocessing was performed on incident description feature. Removal of stopwords, lemmatization and tokenization of the text was performed to use it for our modeling purpouse

  • Data Augmentation & Feature Engineering

    Data augmentation was performed on the complete dataset since there was an imbalance in the data for all the classes in the Critical risk field. The description text was translated into a different language and translated back to English in order to get more variety and more samples for the minority classes. Corrections were made on the misspelt words and generalization was performed for words containing dimensions, lengths, chemical names, etc.

  • Final data for Model

The above steps were re-performed a second time after gaining insights from the initial analysis and the final processed data was used for modeling

Also we only used the Incident description feature for our models because our ultimate goal is to built a chat bot which can only ask for incident description info.

  • Modeling

    • ML Classifiers

      We started modeling with ML classifiers to understand how well normal algorithm performs on the augmented data. We used multiple ML model but finalized on Lgbm, Random Forest Classifier, XGBoost Classifier as they provided best results.

The results provided by ML classifiers were extremely good but on further research we found that these model were a little overfitted. Also in case a new word comes up in the real time testing phase then these models wont be able to perform as expected. Hence we went ahead with neural network & other sophisticated models.

  • Neural Network

    We built a traditional NN model to classify the text description into differnt critical risk. The model results were satisfactory but we decided to increase the model accuracy by using LSTM Model

  • LSTM Model

    We trained and tuned a LSTM model to classify the critical risk. The model after tuning gave best results without overfitting on the existing data. This model will also work well on new description so we decided to stop the modeling with our LSTM model.

  • Model Comparison

    We compared all models on the basis of classification report (Precision, recall, F1 score, their accuracy) & direct comparison of confusion metric of all models. We agreed to use the LSTM model as our final model after comparing all the metrics and the inherent advanteges of LSTM model.

  • Model Limitaion, Closing thoughts & References

    Finally we discuss the current model limitation and steps for future improvement of the model as well as refer all the publication we have taken inspiration from.

def month_quarter_Conversion(x):
    if x in [10, 11, 12]:
        season = 'Fourth'
    elif x in [1, 2, 3]:
        season = 'First'
    elif x in [4, 5, 6]:
        season = 'Second'
    elif x in [7, 8, 9]:
        season = 'Third'
    return season
data['Quarter'] = data['Month'].apply(month_quarter_Conversion)

    ax = fig.add_subplot(121)
    sns.countplot(x = col1, data = df, ax = ax, orient = 'v',

    return plt.show()

When cold weather causes barometric pressure to drop, methane gas can migrate more easily into the mine atmosphere, increasing the risk of an explosion. Dry winter air means drier conditions underground, making it more likely for coal dust to suspend in the mine's atmosphere and create the potential for an explosion.

from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer,PorterStemmer
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS
import nltk
nltk.download('punkt')
nltk.download('wordnet')

def plot_wordcloud(text):
    nltk.download('stopwords')
    stop=set(stopwords.words('english'))

    def _preprocess_text(text):
        corpus=[]
        stem=PorterStemmer()
        lem=WordNetLemmatizer()
        for news in text:
            words=[w for w in word_tokenize(news) if (w not in stop)]

            words=[lem.lemmatize(w) for w in words if len(w)>2]

            corpus.append(words)
        return corpus
    
    corpus=_preprocess_text(text)
    
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white',
        stopwords=set(STOPWORDS),
        max_words=100,
        max_font_size=30, 
        scale=3,
        random_state=1)
    
    wordcloud=wordcloud.generate(str(corpus))

    fig = plt.figure(1, figsize=(12, 12))
    plt.axis('off')
 
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.show()

Data augmentation/Oversampling¶

Since we have a huge imbalance in the classes in our dataset, we will try to generate more samples using translations.

df_translated_full = pd.DataFrame()

# A helper function that selects one of the three translated texts at random
def translate_sentence(sent1, sent2, sent3):
  sentences = [sent1, sent2, sent3]
  this_sent = random.choice(sentences)
  return this_sent

for risk in critical_counts.to_dict('records'):
  new_df = df_translated[df_translated['critical_risk'] == risk['index']].sample(critical_counts_max - risk['critical_risk'], replace=True, random_state=42)
  new_df['description'] = new_df.apply(lambda x: translate_sentence(x.portuguese_translated, x.spanish_translated, x.italian_translated), axis=1)
  df_translated_full = df_translated_full.append(new_df)

df_translated_full.drop(columns=['portuguese_translated', 'italian_translated', 'spanish_translated'], inplace=True)
df = pd.concat([df, df_translated_full], axis=0)
df = df.reset_index().drop(columns=['index'])

Steps involved in oversampling¶

1. Create a copy of the original dataset.
2. Translate the description to a few different languages like Portuguese, Italian and Spanish.
3. Translate the translated text back to English

Why was this done?¶

1. Since there is an imbalance in the data, we need more data sample for the minority classes so that our models are not biased towards the other majority classes.
2. This double stage translation would give us a bit more variety of the same data. Doing this would change the structure of the sentence but not the meaning.

Example:¶

Original:¶
During the execution of the soil sampling task at the Potions area, around 1:15 pm, Luis - WCA, was opening with a machete 
and was bitten by a wasp on the back of his right hand, the same was using at the time of the incident all the EPIs needed 
for activity. The employee was evaluated by the technician who found it to be a mild and localized swelling wound. The 
employee reported that he did not feel any pain and that he could continue the activity.

Data Preprocessing¶

In [ ]:
stop_word_list = list(set(stopwords.words('english'))) # Load standard stop words
stopword_pattern = re.compile(r'\b(' + r'|'.join(stop_word_list) + r')\b\s*') # Compile regex to remove stopwords
df['desc'] = df['description'].str.lower().str.replace('[^a-zA-Z0-9 ]', '', regex=True).str.replace('mx', 'm x ').str.replace(stopword_pattern, ' ', regex=True) # Replace 10cmx20cm to 10cm x 20cm
df['desc'] = df['desc'].str.split(' ')

# Convert words to numbers
def convert_numbers(x):
  new_x = []
  for word in x:
    try:
      word = w2n.word_to_num(word.lower())
    except Exception as e:
      word = word.lower()
    if len(str(word)) > 0: # If the length of the word is zero, then don't return
      new_x.append(str(word))
  return ' '.join(new_x)

df['desc'] = df['desc'].apply(convert_numbers)

# High frequency occuring bigram removal
bigram_stop_pattern = "(i?)(left hand|left foot|left leg|left arm|right hand|right leg|right foot|right arm|time accident|causing the injury|caused the injury|caused injury|causing injury)+"
df["desc"] = df["desc"].str.replace(bigram_stop_pattern, '', regex=True)

# Convert any dimensions like 10cm x 20cm x 30cm to xdimension
dimension_pattern = re.compile(r"(i?)((([\d.]+)\s{0,}(cm|m)\s{0,})+(\s{0,}[x|X]\s{0,}\b|\b))+")
df["desc"] = df["desc"].str.replace(dimension_pattern, ' xdimension ', regex=True)

# Convert weights to xweight
weight_pattern = re.compile(r"(?i)([\d.]+)\s{0,}(lb(s\b|\b)|pound(s\b|\b)|ton(s\b|\b)|kilogram(s\b|\b)|gram(s\b|\b)|ounce(s\b|\b)|oz(s\b|\b)|g(s\b|\b)|gr(s\b|\b)|kg(s\b|\b)|tn(s\b|\b))")
df["desc"] = df["desc"].str.replace(weight_pattern, ' xweight ', regex=True)

# Convert lenghts/heights to xlength
lenght_pattern = re.compile(r"(?i)([\d.]+)\s{0,}(millimeter(s\b|\b)|centimeter(s\b|\b)|meter(s\b|\b)|kilometer(s\b|\b)|mm(s\b|\b)|cm(s\b|\b)|m(s\b|\b)|km(s\b|\b)|mt(s\b|\b)|inch|inches|yard(s\b|\b))")
df["desc"] = df["desc"].str.replace(lenght_pattern, ' xlength ', regex=True)

df['desc'] = df['desc'].str.split(' ')

Preprocessing before lemmatization¶

  1. Any words that represent a number like three or one are converted to their numerical form.

  2. Bigrams that appear very frequently like left hand, right foot, etc. are removed.

  3. Any dimensions like 10cm x 20cm x 30cm or 3m x 6m are converted to a string xdimension

  4. Any words representing weights like 30gm or 152lbs are converted to a string xweight

  5. Any words representing lengths or depths like 5 kilometers or 1 inch are converted to a string xlength

In [ ]:
chemical_names = df_chem['synonyms'].str.lower().to_list() # Get a list of all chemical names
chemical_symbols = df_chem['chemical_formula'].dropna().astype('str').str.lower().to_list() # Get a list of all chemical symbols

Final data preprocessing¶

  1. Convert to lowercase

  2. Correction/conversion of words

  3. Convert chemical names/chemical symbols to 'chemical'

  4. Lemmatize the words

  5. Remove pure numeric words

In [ ]:
df_conversion_dict = {i['ori']:i['convert'] for i in df_conversion.to_dict('records')}

lemma = WordNetLemmatizer()
def convert_words(word): # Word corrections in case of typing mistakes
  if word in df_conversion_dict:
    return df_conversion_dict[word]
  else:
    return word

def convert_chemicals(word): # Convert chemical names/symbols to 'chemical'
  if word in chemical_names or word in chemical_symbols:
    return 'chemical'
  else:
    return word

def stop_word_removal(word): # Remove any stopwords
  if word not in stop_word_list:
    return word
  else:
    return ''

def data_preprocessing(word): # Chain all functions together to perform the data preprocessing
  word = word.lower()
  word = convert_words(word)
  word = convert_chemicals(word)
  word = lemma.lemmatize(word, 'v')
  if word.isnumeric():
    return ''
  return word

Data Vectorization:¶

Count Vectorization¶

Count Vectorization will create a matrix consisting of term/token counts by the number of rows.

In [ ]:
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(1,1))
df_vectorized = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['desc'])

TF-IDF Vectorization¶

  • It is an information retrieval technique that weights a term's frequency TF and its inverse document frequency IDF.

  • Based on the occurance of a term in a document, it will have its own TF and IDF score.

    TF(t) = (Number of times term t appears in a document) / (Total number of terms in the document)
IDF(t) = log_e(Total number of documents / Number of documents with term t in it).
  • A product of these two scores gives us the weight of the term in the document and the higher the score is, the rarer the term is in the given document and vice-versa.

$tfidf( t, d, D ) = tf( t, d ) \times idf( t, D )$

In [ ]:
tf_vec = df_vectorized.toarray()
normalized_tf = tf_vec[2] / np.sqrt(np.sum(tf_vec[2]**2))
tfidf = TfidfTransformer(use_idf=False, norm='l2', smooth_idf=False)
tf_normalized = tfidf.fit_transform(tf_vec)

In [ ]:
encoded_cols = {ix:i for ix,i in enumerate(vectorizer.get_feature_names())}

y_test_conv = pd.get_dummies(y_countVec_test)
classes = y_test_conv.columns
classes = [i.replace('critical_risk_', '') for i in classes]
label_mapping = {i:ix for ix, i in enumerate(classes)}

def train_ml_classifier(df, clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, overfit_check=False, model_name=''):
  clf.fit(X_train, y_train)  

  y_pred=clf.predict(X_train)
  print(f"Train score: {round(accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred) * 100)} %")
  if overfit_check:
    print(clf)
    print("Training Classification report: \n{}\n".format(
      classification_report(y_train, y_pred)))
  
  y_pred=clf.predict(X_test)
  print("Testing Classification report: \n{}\n".format(
    classification_report(y_test, y_pred)))
  
  
  cols = list(df.columns)
  cols.remove('critical_risk')
  cols = [encoded_cols[col] if col in encoded_cols else col[:8] + '\n' + col[8:] for col in cols]

  try:
    clf.feature_importances_
    plt.figure(figsize=(35,5));
    sns.barplot(data=pd.DataFrame(dict(zip(cols,clf.feature_importances_)), index=[1]).T.reset_index().sort_values(1, ascending=False).head(30), x="index", y=1, palette='cividis');
  except:
    pass

  act_pred_df = pd.DataFrame({'Actual' : y_test['critical_risk'].to_numpy(), 'Predicted' : y_pred})
  act_pred_df['Model'] = model_name
  act_pred_df['Actual'] = act_pred_df['Actual'].replace(label_mapping)
  act_pred_df['Predicted'] = act_pred_df['Predicted'].replace(label_mapping)

  return clf, y_pred, act_pred_df

Neural network¶

In [ ]:
def build_nn_model(model_layers, optimizer, loss_type):
    model = Sequential()
    for layer in model_layers:
        model.add(layer)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss=loss_type, metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

def lr_scheduler(epoch, lr):
    decay_rate = 0.1
    decay_step = 90
    if epoch % decay_step == 0 and epoch:
        return lr * decay_rate
    return lr
In [ ]:
def train_model(nn_model, target_col, epochs, X, y, lr, momentum):
    num_classes = int(y.nunique())

    y_conv = pd.get_dummies(y[target_col])
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y_conv, test_size=0.3, train_size=0.7, random_state=42)

    print(nn_model.summary())

    model_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(f'text_classifier_{target_col}.pkl',
                                                    save_best_only=True, 
                                                    monitor='val_accuracy', 
                                                    mode='max', 
                                                    verbose = 1)

    lrs = LearningRateScheduler(lr_scheduler, verbose=1)

    model_history = nn_model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data = (X_test, y_test), epochs=epochs, batch_size=16, verbose= 1, callbacks=[model_checkpoint])

    nn_model = tf.keras.models.load_model(f'text_classifier_{target_col}.pkl')

    predictions = nn_model.predict(X_test)
    y_test_conv = pd.get_dummies(y_test)
    label_mapping = np.argmax(y_test_conv.to_numpy(), axis=-1)

    print("Classification report: \n{}\n".format(
        classification_report(label_mapping, np.argmax(predictions, axis=-1))))

    return nn_model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test

from sklearn import metrics

def conf_mat(y_test, y_pred,mod):
  index_cols=["Bees/Venomous Animals","Blocking and isolation of energies","Fall","Hazards during Electrical installations","Injuries/Cuts","Manual Tools",
  "NA","Others","Power lock","Pressed","Pressurized Systems/ Chemical Substances","Projections of fragments","Suspended Loads","Vehicles and Mobile Equipment"]

  preds_cols=["Predicted Bees/Venomous Animals","Predicted Blocking and isolation of energies","Predicted Fall","Predicted Hazards during Electrical installations",
  "Predicted Injuries/Cuts","Predicted Manual Tools","Predicted NA","Predicted Others","Predicted Power lock","Predicted Pressed","Predicted Pressurized Systems/ Chemical Substances",
  "Predicted Projections of fragments","Predicted Suspended Loads","Predicted Vehicles and Mobile Equipment"]
  model_name="Confusion Matrix for "+mod
  cm2=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
  df_cm2 = pd.DataFrame(cm2, index = [i for i in index_cols],
                    columns = [i for i in preds_cols])
  plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
  #figure, axes = plt.figure(nrows=4, ncols=2, figsize=(20,20))
  plt.title(model_name)
  sns.heatmap(df_cm2, annot=True);

Final Thoughts¶

Data:¶

  • We discovered that the main causes of accidents are mistakes in hand-operation and time-related factor as evident by the bi-gram analysis.

  • To reduce the occurrences of accidents, more stringent safety standards in hand-operation will be needed in period when many accidents occur. With more detailed information such as machining data(ex. CNC, Current, Voltage) in plants, weather information, employee's personal data(ex. age, experience in the industry sector, work performance ), we can clarify the cause of accidents more correctly.

  • The data has inherent imbalance which in turn makes it difficult to predict the severity of incidents

Model Finalization:¶

  • The LSTM model has the highest combined accuracy on train and validation dataset
  • LSTM model also performs best in terms of precision, recall & F1 score It also don’t have dependency on the bag of words present in the dataset.
  • Also as seen in the comparison of confusion matrix the LSTM classification results are better than other models

Since LSTM performs overall well in all metrics and is not overfitting on the training dataset we will go ahead with LSTM as our final model.

Model Limitation:¶

  • While LSTM does perform best out of existing models, the overall modeling can be improved with balanced data set and inclusion of a bigger corpus that doesn’t have dependency on current text only.

  • Also we only used the Incident description feature for our models because our ultimate goal is to build a chat bot which can only ask for incident description info.

Chat Bot UI¶

  • Please refer to the gdrive link (link below) or the zip file shared to use flask based chatbot UI https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Qczd1CxlOi5pjCfmq0rPUVDauVQ5EvKw/view?usp=sharing

Steps to Use the Chat Bot:¶

  • For the python packages required to run the Flask app, please refer to the requirements.txt file in the root location.

  • To run the chatbot application, open command prompt in the root location of the Flask application and run the command "python app.py". This file is there in the zip file mentioned above.

  • Once the application starts, on the browser, open http://localhost:5000

  • On the chatbot application, input the accident description in the text box provided to get the critical risk category , the mean accident level and the mean potential accident level. Some of the description is mentioned below.

  • Typing "bye" in the text box ends the chat and shows a button "Chat again?" which can be clicked to continue the chat.

Sample Input for chatbot:¶

  • When averaging 04:30 am, the operator Daniel removed cleaning accessories under the mobile channel of line 01, for which he supported his left hand on the rail that was in motion. At that moment the crushing of the 2nd finger of the left hand occurs; the injury occurs. The collaborator is referred to the Medical for care.

  • During the marking of the management points, the supervision and the breeders enter the work to carry out the ventilation inspection, for which the surveying work stops to turn on the fan and proceed with the air flow measurements. When the fan is turned on due to pressure, it breaks the fastening points of the toe and the sleeve falls to the floor generating a chicoteo from gable to gable, product of the chicoteo a fragment of the aggregate of the shocrete is projected on the face of the injure
